9L10.8752 19.9981C10.8576 19.9893 10.8423 19.9763 10.8309 19.9602C10.8195 19.9441 10.8122 19.9254 10.8098 19.9058V10.6071C10.8107 9.18295 11.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>The texts provided summarize the works of Jürgen Schmidhuber, a computer scientist known for his work in artificial intelligence, specifically in the areas of creativity, curiosity, and motivation.</p><p>He proposes a framework for building a creative system. The system includes a predictor or compressor (e.g., a Recurrent Neural Network or RNN) that constantly learns from a growing history of actions and sensory inputs, essentially encapsulating the known behavior of the world. This system also includes an intrinsic reward mechanism that measures the improvement of the predictor or compressor. These rewards are then processed by a reinforcement learning algorithm, which generates actions or behaviors expected to maximize future rewards.</p><p>This approach suggests that a creative agent could be motivated to discover novel patterns and make them predictable or compressible, thereby maximizing learning progress.</p><p>Schmidhuber's work is centered around the idea of compression progress, which he argues is the driving force behind subjective concepts such as beauty, novelty, surprise, interestingness, curiosity, and creativity. He extends this idea to art, science, music, and jokes, suggesting that the intrinsic fun or joy an observer derives from a sequence of actions and observations is related to the reduction in resources required to encode the data before and after learning.</p><p>In his PowerPlay model, he focuses on training an increasingly general problem solver by continually searching for the simplest unsolved problem.</p><p>Schmidhuber's work provides a formal and computational perspective on creativity and could have significant implications for the development of advanced AI systems.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a2 2 0 0 1-2-2V6a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h2"></path><rect x="8" y="2" width="8" height="4" rx="1" ry="1"></rect></svg></button><div class="flex gap-1"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M14 9V5a3 3 0 0 0-3-3l-4 9v11h11.28a2 2 0 0 0 2-1.7l1.38-9a2 2 0 0 0-2-2.3zM7 22H4a2 2 0 0 1-2-2v-7a2 2 0 0 1 2-2h3"></path></svg></button><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M10 15v4a3 3 0 0 0 3 3l4-9V2H5.72a2 2 0 0 0-2 1.7l-1.38 9a2 2 0 0 0 2 2.3zm7-13h2.67A2.31 2.31 0 0 1 22 4v7a2.31 2.31 0 0 1-2.33 2H17"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 dark:bg-gray-800"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><div class="flex-shrink-0 flex flex-col relative items-end"><div class="w-[30px]"><div class="relative flex"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; position: relative; max-width: 100%;"><span style="box-sizing: border-box; display: block; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; max-width: 100%;"><img alt="" aria-hidden="true" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=%27http://www.w3.org/2000/svg%27%20version=%271.1%27%20width=%2738%27%20height=%2738%27/%3e" style="display: block; max-width: 100%; width: initial; height: initial; background: none; opacity: 1; border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px;"></span><img alt="User" src="https://chat.openai.com/_next/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Flh3.googleusercontent.com%2Fa%2FAGNmyxbfUJGaUXxADgtF19b5ZhmrVKp8-tY9hQf2Jfmp%3Ds96-c&amp;w=96&amp;q=75" decoding="async" data-nimg="intrinsic" class="rounded-sm" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" width="30" height="30"></span></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"> A Short 𝘏𝘪𝘴𝘵𝘰𝘳𝘺 𝘰𝘧 𝘈𝘐

Heloise d'Argenteui advocates "Faking it until you make it" although she doesn't use that exact quote (1130-1132)

Giordano Bruno publishes the theory of the infinite universes (1584)

Zara Yacob proposes a form of internalism and subjectivity in epistemology (1667)

Jeanne-Marie Bouvier de la Motte-Guyon (Madame Guyon) advocates Quietism and writes "A Short and Very Easy Method of Prayer" (1685)

Emanuel Swedenborg explores the relationship between the spiritual and physical worlds, and publicises the concept of correspondences (1688-1772)

Immanuel Kant develops the concept of transcendental idealism and the categorical imperative in ethics (1724-1804)

Thomas Bayes writes the theory named after him in his journal, but he hides it and tells no one (1736)

Benjamin Franklin invents the Book Reaching Device (1786)

Charles Darwin works on developing the theory of evolution through natural selection (1809-1882)

William James develops the concept of pragmatism and studies consciousness (1842-1910)

Ada Lovelace writes the first computer program, but none is available to run it (1843)

Henri Bergson explores the nature of time and consciousness and develops the concept of élan vital (1859-1941)

Wilhelm Wundt establishes the first psychology laboratory at the University of Leipzig (1879)

Sigmund Freud publishes "The Interpretation of Dreams" (1900)

Maria Montessori cuts letters out of little pieces of paper (1907)

Srinivasa Ramanujan publishes "Some Properties of Bernoulli's Numbers" (1911)

Jorge Luis Borges dreams he sees a book titled, "The Timeless Wisdom of the Sphinx", but he is too afraid to look inside (1922)

Cecilia Payne-Gaposchkin discovers the chemical composition of stars (1925)

Graham Wallas asks himself "How can I know what I think until I see what I say?" (1926)

Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts publish "A Logical Calculus of Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity," proposing the first artificial neuron (1943)

Norbert Wiener popularizes the idea of cybernetics (1948)

Vannevar Bush invents the concept of the Memex, a hypothetical machine that can store and retrieve information (1945)

Ilya Prigogine publishes "Thermodynamic Study of Irreversible Phenomena" (1947)

B.F. Skinner develops behaviorism and writes "Walden Two" (1948)

Jean Piaget explains his theory of cognitive development (1952)

Niklas Luhmann reinvents the Zettelkasten (1954)

John McCarthy, Marvin Minsky, Nathaniel Rochester, and Claude Shannon organize the Dartmouth Conference, coining the term "artificial intelligence" and laying the groundwork for the field (1956)

Noam Chomsky develops the theory of generative grammar (1957)

William Powers develops perceptual control theory (1958)

Arthur Samuel creates the first machine learning program, a checkers-playing program (1959)

Marvin Minsky co-founds the MIT AI lab (1959)

Joseph Weizenbaum creates the natural language processing program ELIZA, designed to simulate conversation with a therapist (1967)

Torey Hayden writes about her experiences as a special education teacher and therapist (1970s-1990s)

Humberto Maturana and Francisco Varela publish Autopoiesis and Cognition: The Realization of the Living (1972)

Paul Werbos invents backpropagation, a key algorithm for training neural networks (1974)

Gerald Edelman and Rodney Brooks create the first autonomous robot, named Shakey (1981)

Benoit Mandelbrot describes the fractal bearing his name (1982)

Geoffrey Hinton and David Rumelhart develop the backpropagation algorithm for neural networks (1986)

Jürgen Schmidhuber develops the theory of artificial curiosity (1987) and Long Short-Term Memory algorithm, a key architecture for recurrent neural networks (1995)

Judea Pearl uses the term Markov Blanket to refer to a probabilistic shield (1988)

Sejnowski and Rosenberg demonstrate the use of evolutionary algorithms for training neural networks (1991)

Alison Gopnik publishes "How We Know Our Minds: The Illusion of First-Person Knowledge of Intentionality" (1993)

Yoshua Bengio and colleagues develop the first deep neural network for language processing (2006)

Peter Carruthers writes something like "We do not have privileged access to our own attitudes" (2011)</div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="p-1 rounded-md hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M11 4H4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v14a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h14a2 2 0 0 0 2-2v-7"></path><path d="M18.5 2.5a2.121 2.121 0 0 1 3 3L12 15l-4 1 1-4 9.5-9.5z"></path></svg></button></div></div></div></div></div><div class="group w-full text-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 border-b border-black/10 dark:border-gray-900/50 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-[#444654]"><div class="flex p-4 gap-4 text-base md:gap-6 md:max-w-2xl lg:max-w-xl xl:max-w-3xl md:py-6 lg:px-0 m-auto"><di