3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>In mathematics, a "ball" refers to a specific shape or topological space. In this context, when the authors state that the totally nonnegative Grassmannian is a ball, they mean that it is homeomorphic to a closed ball.</p><p>A closed ball is a geometric shape consisting of all points that are at most a certain distance away from a given center point. It is a convex set and can be thought of as the interior and boundary of a solid sphere. In topology, a closed ball is a fundamental example of a compact space.</p><p>When the authors assert that the totally nonnegative Grassmannian is a ball, they are claiming that it shares certain topological properties with a closed ball. Specifically, they have established a homeomorphism between the totally nonnegative Grassmannian and a closed ball of a certain dimension. This means that the two spaces are essentially the same from a topological perspective, and they have similar geometric properties.</p><p>The characterization of the totally nonnegative Grassmannian as a ball provides valuable insights into its structure and allows researchers to apply tools and techniques from the theory of balls and their properties to study this particular space in topological combinatorics.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-wh