er to specific learning strategies employed by artificial neural networks.</p><p>Stubbornness refers to the persistence or resilience of the neural network in retaining its current beliefs or internal representations. Despite receiving incorrect answers from an unreliable teacher, the network does not immediately discard its existing knowledge but remains steadfast in its current understanding. This stubbornness allows the network to be cautious about updating its internal representations too quickly based on unreliable information.</p><p>Introspection, on the other hand, involves the neural network reflecting on its own learning behavior and extracting useful information from it. The network observes patterns or trends in its own learning process, such as the frequency or consistency of incorrect answers, and utilizes this self-reflective information to adjust its internal representations. By being introspective, the network can gain insights into the reliability or accuracy of its own learning process, which can help it make more informed decisions about when and how to update its internal knowledge.</p><p>Together, stubbornness and introspection form a learning strategy that allows the neural network to navigate learning under imperfect conditions. The network is persistent in retaining its existing beliefs while being introspective about its own learning behavior, which enables it to adapt and improve its internal representations over time. This strategy helps the network become wiser than its unreliable teacher and enhance its generalization abilities.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xml