parameter, as well as dimensions and distances. The hierarchy of the algorithm has incremental dimensionality, with search levels, parameter levels, and pattern levels. Cross-comparison and clustering occur at different levels, and patterns with above-average match to their nearest neighbors are clustered into higher-level patterns. The concept of incremental range and derivation is introduced, with larger kernels and Laplacian used for incremental range and derivation on the pixel level.</p><p>Feedback plays a role in the algorithm, with average match being the first order of value filter computed on higher levels. Positional filters, such as pixel size and kernel size, determine external dimensions of the input. The filters represent co-averages to a higher-level average value, and clustering is based on the deviation from those filters. Positive patterns are formed, containing input elements that are novel and similar to each other, making them predictive of future input.</p><p>The hierarchy of the cognitive algorithm is described as a single global hierarchy where feedforward inputs and feedback filters pass through the same levels of search and composition. Each higher level is a nested hierarchy, and sub-hierarchies are generated sequentially based on elevation in a higher-order hierarchy. The author also mentions the combination of sensory and motor hierarchies into one within their scheme, with positional filter patterns serving as the equivalent of motor patterns.</p><p>Please note that the provided excerpt is a technical description of the author's cognitive algorithm, and the full content on the website may provide further details and explanations.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox