shape or morphological degrees of freedom, and limited free energy, will naturally evolve towards a neuromorphic morphology under the constraints of the free energy principle.</p><p>According to the free energy principle, systems tend to minimize the difference between their internal states and the states that generate sensory inputs. In the context of neuromorphic computing, this principle leads to the development of hierarchical computations, where each level of the hierarchy performs coarse-graining of inputs and fine-graining of outputs. These hierarchical structures are observed in various biological systems, ranging from intracellular signal transduction pathways to the organization of perception and action cycles in the mammalian brain.</p><p>The article also discusses the formal connections between cone-cocone diagrams (CCCD), which model quantum reference frames, and topological quantum field theories. These connections enable the representation of hierarchical computations within the framework of topological quantum neural networks.</p><p>Overall, the article highlights how the free energy principle and the concept of neuromorphic development can provide insights into the organization and functioning of biological systems, as well as inform the design of neuromorphic computing systems inspired by biological principles.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-