6C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>Perceptual Control Theory (PCT) is a psychological framework that seeks to explain human behavior and cognition by focusing on the process of controlling perceptions. It proposes that individuals engage in continuous goal-directed behavior to maintain a desired state of perception.</p><p>Here are some key points and concepts related to Perceptual Control Theory:</p><ol><li><p>Perceptual Control: According to PCT, individuals are motivated to maintain a specific perception or experience. This perception can encompass various aspects of their environment, such as their physical surroundings, social interactions, or internal states. People engage in behavior to control and shape their perceptions to align with their goals.</p></li><li><p>Feedback Loops: PCT emphasizes the role of feedback loops in maintaining and adjusting perceptions. Individuals continuously monitor the gap between their desired perception and the actual perception they are experiencing. Based on this feedback, they engage in behavior to close this gap and bring their perception closer to their desired state.</p></li><li><p>Comparators: Comparators are internal reference signals that individuals use to evaluate and compare their desired perception with the actual perception. These comparators serve as a standard against which deviations are measured. When there is a discrepancy, individuals engage in actions to bring their perceptions back in line with their goals.</p></li><li><p>Control Systems: PCT proposes that humans have control systems that regulate and adjust behavior to achieve and maintain desired perceptions. These control systems operate based on the information provided by feedback loops and comparators. They generate corrective actions to minimize the difference between the desired and actual perceptions.</p></li><li><p>Hierarchy of Control: PCT suggests that control processes operate hierarchically, with higher-level control systems influencing and coordinating lower-level control systems. This hierarchy allows for the integration of multiple perceptions and goals into a cohesive system of control.</p></li><li><p>Adaptation and Learning: PCT emphasizes that individuals learn and adapt based on the feedback they receive from their control processes. Through trial and error, people adjust their actions to achieve more accurate and consistent control over their perceptions. Learning involves refining the internal models and representations of the environment to improve control.</p></li></ol><p>In summary, Perceptual Control Theory proposes that individuals engage in continuous goal-directed behavior to control and shape their perceptions. By monitoring feedback, comparing perceptions to desired states, and engaging in corrective actions, individuals strive to maintain and adapt their perceptions to align with their goals.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disa