ords dark:prose-invert light"><p>Grammatical recursion refers to the ability of a language to embed clauses or phrases within other clauses or phrases, creating a hierarchical structure. It involves the use of recursive rules that allow for the repetition or nesting of linguistic elements. In simple terms, it is the ability to build complex sentences by embedding one part within another.</p><p>For example, consider the sentence: "The cat that chased the mouse that ate the cheese is black." This sentence contains a recursive structure where the relative clause "that chased the mouse that ate the cheese" is embedded within the main clause.</p><p>Grammatical recursion allows for the generation of an infinite number of sentences by recursively applying syntactic rules. This feature is considered a fundamental aspect of human language and is thought to be present in most languages around the world.</p><p>The debate surrounding the existence of grammatical recursion in the Pirahã language arises from the claim that it lacks the ability to form recursive structures like those found in many other languages. This challenges the notion that all human languages universally possess grammatical recursion.</p><p>Further research and analysis are necessary to better understand the precise nature and extent of recursion in different languages and its implications for our understanding of human language capabilities.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled=