 break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>You raise a valid point. Linguistic claims about a language, including those about Pirahã, should ideally be based on extensive research and analysis of a large corpus of language data. A comprehensive understanding of a language requires thorough documentation and analysis of its phonetics, phonology, morphology, syntax, and semantics.</p><p>It is true that some linguistic features may not be immediately apparent without a significant amount of data. The intricacies of a language's grammar and structure often emerge through in-depth studies conducted over an extended period of time, involving extensive fieldwork and analysis of a wide range of linguistic contexts.</p><p>While the claims made about Pirahã, such as its unique sound system or verb structure, are based on the available research and observations of linguists who have worked closely with the language, further research and investigation are necessary to confirm and refine these findings. The linguistic community continually strives to deepen its understanding of languages through ongoing research and collaboration.</p><p>Therefore, it is important to approach linguistic claims with a critical and open mind, acknowledging that our knowledge of any given language is always subject to revision and refinement as new data and insights emerge.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:t